        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="sga" resp="#NW">
                 <ab>
                     <lb n="1"/>ᚁᚐᚅᚋᚐᚉᚐᚔ<unclear reason="faded">ᚂ</unclear><g ref="#forfid_X"/>
                 </ab>
             </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="sga" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>BANMACAI<unclear reason="faded">L</unclear><g ref="#forfid_X" type="interpretation_E"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1"><note>The letter before the X-forfid could be read as V, with 3 rather than two strokes.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation"/>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Moore (Sikora and Moore 2020, 78) suggests that <q>the reading <foreign xml:lang="sga">Ban Macaile</foreign> could mean fair, pure, holy or blessed Macaile</q> and historically MacCaille is associated with Croghan Hill (Cruachu of Brí Éile) in Offaly which overlooks Lemanaghan Bog. However, this interpretation is not entirely straightforward.</p>
            </div>
